## Architecture Decision: Notion MCP vs. notion-client SDK

> [!NOTE]
> You asked: *"Why do we need notion-client if we use MCP for Notion?"* — Here's the full trade-off:

| | `notion-client` SDK | Notion MCP |
|---|---|---|
| **What it is** | Python library calling Notion REST API directly | A running server process that exposes Notion as tools to an **LLM agent** |
| **Designed for** | Python scripts, CLIs, backend services | AI assistants (Claude, Gemini) issuing tool-calls in a conversation |
| **How called** | `import notion_client; client.pages.create(...)` | LLM generates `{"tool": "create_page", "args": {...}}` → MCP routes it |
| **Token location** | Your `.env` file | MCP server config (already done ✅) |
| **Works in a Python CLI?** | ✅ Yes — clean, synchronous, easy to test | ❌ No — requires spawning & connecting to an MCP subprocess, adds ~200 lines of JSON-RPC plumbing |
| **Testability** | Easy to mock | Hard to mock (need running MCP process) |
| **Overhead** | ~0ms | MCP process startup + IPC per call |

**Decision: Use `notion-client` SDK** for our Python agents. The MCP server is perfect when *you* or an AI assistant runs `chromemind` interactively — but the CLI code itself should call the API directly. Your MCP token and the SDK token are **the same token** — you just copy it to `.env` once.

> [!TIP]
> **How to find your Notion Database ID:**
> 1. Open your Notion database in a browser.
> 2. The URL looks like: `https://www.notion.so/yourworkspace/`**`abc123def456...`**`?v=...`
> 3. The 32-character string between the last `/` and `?v=` is your database ID.
> 4. Or: Share → Copy link → the long hex string is the ID.

